The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 New Delhi: Hours before the end of the deadline, world champion boxer M.C. Mary Kom was Thursday recommended for this years Rajiv Gandhi Khel Ratna the countrys highest sporting honour. The light-flyweight pugilist, who has a record of three straight world titles to her credit, filed her application with the Indian Amateur Boxing Federation (IABF) on Thursday and the organisation forwarded it to the sports ministry just before the deadline, IABF executive director said.

 Zurich: Sepp Blatter was given a third term as president of the world soccers governing body by acclamation after standing as the only candidate at Thursdays Fifa Congress. I accept this mandate and I thank you for your continuing trust in me, he told delegates from Fifas 208 member associations, who gave him a four-year term until 2011.

 Milan: Sampdoria striker Francesco Flachi has been banned from soccer for 16 months after testing positive for cocaine, the Serie A club said on Thursday. Flachi was already suspended pending the final decision by a disciplinary commission. The 32-year-old tested positive for a metabolite of cocaine after a home game with Inter Milan on January 28. The striker has been in trouble with the football authorities before.

 Paris: Leading strikers Thierry Henry and Andriy Shevchenko will be missing from Frances Euro 2008 qualifier at home to Ukraine on Saturday when both sides will be looking to take command of Group B. Henry has been ruled out with a groin injury. Shevchenko is missing for Ukraine after undergoing hernia surgery earlier this month.

 Mount Pleasant (US): Teenage prodigy MacKinzie Kline achieved a long-cherished dream when she made her LPGA debut at Ginn Tribute on Thursday. The 15-year-old American has continually defied the odds after being born with a congenital heart defect. Im very nervous playing with all these great golfers, Kline said.

 Hong Kong: China is backtracking on promises of greater freedoms for foreign media, a human rights group said Thursday. The Chinese government is already failing to deliver on its pledge to fully lift restrictions for foreign journalists ahead of the Beijing Games, the groups deputy Asia director said in a statement.

